<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41797570</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>09</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">2056-4694</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>09</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>BJPsych bulletin</Title><ISOAbbreviation>BJPsych Bull</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Language matters: discourses of therapeutic optimism and recovery in the treatment of eating disorders.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1</StartPage><EndPage>7</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1-7</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1192/bjb.2026.10214</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="AIMS AND METHOD" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This article explores how clinical language used to describe long-standing and severe eating disorders shapes treatment experiences and outcomes. Drawing on critical discourse theory and the authors' lived experiences, the paper analyses the impacts of language through intrapersonal, interpersonal and systemic lenses.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The analysis highlights how the language used to describe&#xa0;illness can foster therapeutic nihilism, internalised hopelessness and disengagement from treatment for both clinicians and patients, reducing the impetus for developing or accessing better care. These labels may obscure systemic shortcomings in treatment provision&#xa0;and can become self-fulfilling, undermining clinician motivation and patient recovery.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CLINICAL IMPLICATIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The authors propose a paradigm shift toward recovery-oriented, co-created language that centres epistemic justice. Clinical discourse should promote therapeutic optimism and support inclusive, patient-centred care. Recovery-focused language can strengthen engagement, improve outcomes and support a treatment culture grounded in mutual respect and hope.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Downs</LastName><ForeName>James</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-4321-8574</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Person with Lived Experience, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Adams</LastName><ForeName>Marissa</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Person with Lived Experience, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Carnegie</LastName><ForeName>Anna</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Person with Lived Experience, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>09</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>England</Country><MedlineTA>BJPsych Bull</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101650950</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2056-4694</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Feeding or eating disorders</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">diagnosis and classification</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">education and training</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">patients and service users</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">stigma and discrimination</Keyword></KeywordList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>9</Day><Hour>7</Hour><Minute>41</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>9</Day><Hour>7</Hour><Minute>41</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>9</Day><Hour>4</Hour><Minute>33</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><Pub